{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01L62SHjFDpeDN1Ko1tuWb6d","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01Fsh1jfhseyb3qRAQdzM3yF","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS_EOF'\nELASTICSEARCH SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\nDate: 2026-06-16\nCluster: elasticsearch (3-node, version 8.11.1)\nAuditor: Read-only automated audit — no changes made\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nCRITICAL FINDINGS\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n[CRIT-1] AUTHENTICATION DISABLED (xpack.security.enabled: false)\n  xpack.security.enabled is explicitly set to false in the running\n  elasticsearch.yml (ConfigMap: es-config). The cluster accepts ALL\n  requests from ANY source without credentials. The elastic-password\n  secret is provisioned but is not enforced by the cluster.\n  Impact: Full unauthenticated read/write access to all indices.\n\n[CRIT-2] HTTP API SERVED OVER PLAINTEXT (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: false)\n  The Elasticsearch HTTP API (port 9200) is served over plain HTTP.\n  All queries, responses, index data, and cluster management traffic\n  is transmitted without encryption.\n  Impact: Full data exposure to any network observer inside the cluster.\n\n[CRIT-3] INTER-NODE TRANSPORT UNENCRYPTED (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: false)\n  Node-to-node communication on port 9300 (shard replication, cluster\n  state, discovery) is unencrypted. All three nodes confirmed this\n  setting: xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled=false.\n  Impact: An attacker with pod network access can intercept or inject\n  into cluster-internal traffic.\n\n[CRIT-4] DELIBERATE SECURITY REGRESSION FROM INTENDED CONFIGURATION\n  The kubectl.kubernetes.io/last-applied-configuration annotation on\n  ConfigMap es-config proves the cluster was originally deployed with:\n    xpack.security.enabled: true\n    xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true  (cert paths configured)\n    xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true  (cert paths + verification_mode: certificate)\n  The running configuration has all three settings disabled. This is\n  not drift — it is a deliberate post-deploy downgrade of the security\n  posture. Authorization for this change must be verified.\n\n[CRIT-5] AUTH-CHECKER HEALTH MONITOR FAILING DUE TO SECURITY DOWNGRADE\n  Deployment auth-checker (pod auth-checker-75bf86d678-z2dfz) is\n  0/1 Ready (MinimumReplicasUnavailable). Its readiness probe attempts\n  HTTPS authentication against /_security/_authenticate. With auth and\n  TLS disabled, the probe cannot succeed. This confirms CRIT-4: the\n  monitoring component that would detect an unauthenticated cluster is\n  itself broken by the configuration change.\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nHIGH FINDINGS\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n[HIGH-1] NO KUBERNETES NETWORKPOLICY IN NAMESPACE\n  Zero NetworkPolicy objects exist in the elasticsearch namespace.\n  Any pod anywhere in the cluster (including untrusted workloads in\n  other namespaces) can reach port 9200 (HTTP API) and port 9300\n  (transport) with no restriction.\n  Baseline: Ingress to port 9200 should be restricted to authorized\n  namespaces/pods; port 9300 should be cluster-internal only.\n\n[HIGH-2] PRIVILEGED INIT CONTAINER\n  StatefulSet es runs an init container (image: busybox) with\n  securityContext.privileged: true to set vm.max_map_count=262144.\n  A privileged container has unrestricted access to the host kernel.\n  Baseline: Use a DaemonSet or node tuning operator to set sysctl on\n  nodes rather than granting pod-level privilege.\n\n[HIGH-3] NO POD SECURITY CONTEXT ON ELASTICSEARCH CONTAINERS\n  The main elasticsearch container spec has securityContext: {}.\n  No runAsNonRoot enforcement, no readOnlyRootFilesystem, no\n  capability drops (e.g., drop: [ALL]), no seccomp profile.\n  The container may run as root with full Linux capabilities.\n\n[HIGH-4] CLUSTER BOUND TO ALL INTERFACES (network.host: 0.0.0.0)\n  Elasticsearch binds HTTP and transport to 0.0.0.0 on every node.\n  Combined with absent NetworkPolicy (HIGH-1), this maximizes\n  reachability from any pod in the cluster.\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nMEDIUM FINDINGS\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n[MED-1] INGRESS TLS OFFLOADING ONLY — NOT END-TO-END ENCRYPTION\n  Ingress elasticsearch has TLS configured (secretName: es-ingress-tls)\n  with nginx.ingress.kubernetes.io/force-ssl-redirect: true and\n  ssl-redirect: true. External clients get HTTPS. However, the ingress\n  controller connects to es-http:9200 over plain HTTP. Traffic is\n  decrypted at the ingress and travels unencrypted inside the cluster\n  network. With CRIT-2 (HTTP TLS disabled), end-to-end TLS is not\n  possible in the current state.\n\n[MED-2] INCOMPLETE PASSWORD ROTATION — TWO CREDENTIAL SECRETS PRESENT\n  Two password secrets coexist:\n    elastic-password      (age ~57m at audit time)\n    elastic-password-next (age ~40m at audit time)\n  The -next secret indicates a rotation was initiated but not completed\n  or cleaned up. The current active credential is unknown; if the old\n  password was not invalidated, both may grant access (though auth is\n  currently disabled — see CRIT-1). The -next secret should be\n  reconciled or removed once rotation is completed.\n\n[MED-3] ALL NODES ARE MASTER-ELIGIBLE WITH ALL ROLES\n  All three nodes carry roles: data, data_cold, data_content,\n  data_frozen, data_hot, data_warm, ingest, master, ml,\n  remote_cluster_client, transform. There are no dedicated master\n  nodes. In production, dedicated master nodes (not holding data)\n  reduce the blast radius of a compromised data node and improve\n  cluster stability under heavy load.\n\n[MED-4] NO AUDIT LOGGING CONFIGURED\n  No xpack.security.audit.enabled setting is present. Even after\n  re-enabling xpack.security, access audit trails will not be generated\n  without explicit audit configuration. Compliance frameworks (SOC 2,\n  PCI-DSS, HIPAA) typically require audit logs for data access.\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nLOW FINDINGS\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n[LOW-1] ELASTICSEARCH VERSION 8.11.1 (November 2023) — NOT CURRENT\n  The running version is 8.11.1 (build 2023-11-11). Multiple newer\n  8.x patch releases have been made since then, some addressing\n  security CVEs. Upgrade path should be evaluated against the\n  current 8.x release.\n\n[LOW-2] TEST INDEX IN CLUSTER\n  Index test-index exists with 1 document and a non-default shard\n  allocation setting (routing.allocation.include._tier_preference:\n  data_content). The index name suggests a development artifact.\n  Confirm whether this index is intentional in this environment;\n  if not, it represents unnecessary data exposure surface.\n\n[LOW-3] READINESS PROBE DOWNGRADED ALONGSIDE SECURITY CONFIG\n  The StatefulSet's originally applied readiness probe used HTTPS with\n  credentials:\n    curl -sk ... -u \"elastic:${ELASTIC_PASSWORD}\" https://localhost:9200/...\n  The current running probe uses plain HTTP with no credentials:\n    curl -s ... http://localhost:9200/_cluster/health\n  This confirms the security config was changed after initial deploy.\n  The probe should be restored to use HTTPS+auth once security is\n  re-enabled.\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nINFORMATIONAL\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n\n[INFO-1] LICENSE: Basic (active). Security features are available\n  under Basic license. The only blocker to re-enabling authentication\n  and TLS is the explicit configuration choice to disable them.\n\n[INFO-2] TLS CERTIFICATES PROVISIONED BUT UNUSED\n  Secret es-http-tls (type: Opaque) contains ca.crt, tls.crt, and\n  tls.key. These were generated specifically for Elasticsearch HTTP\n  and transport TLS and are mounted into the pods at\n  /usr/share/elasticsearch/config/certs/. They are valid and ready\n  for use but are bypassed by the disabled security settings.\n\n[INFO-3] CLUSTER HEALTH: green (3/3 nodes, 4 active shards, 0\n  unassigned). Operationally healthy. Active shards: .security-7\n  (primary on es-1, replica on es-0) and test-index (primary on\n  es-2, replica on es-0).\n\n[INFO-4] CLUSTER SETTINGS: No persistent or transient cluster-level\n  settings are configured (both maps are empty). Default values apply\n  for all cluster settings including IP filtering and shard allocation.\n\n[INFO-5] DISCOVERY / INITIAL MASTER NODES: cluster.initial_master_nodes\n  is set to es-0,es-1,es-2. This setting is only relevant on first\n  cluster bootstrap and has no effect on a running cluster, but it\n  should be removed or left as-is per Elasticsearch docs.\n\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\nSUMMARY — REMEDIATION PRIORITY ORDER\n════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════\n1. [CRIT-4] Investigate and authorize (or revert) the security\n   configuration downgrade before any other remediation.\n2. [CRIT-1,2,3] Re-enable xpack.security.enabled, HTTP SSL, and\n   transport SSL using the already-provisioned certificates in\n   es-http-tls. Update the readiness probe (LOW-3) at the same time.\n3. [HIGH-1] Apply NetworkPolicy to restrict port 9200 to authorized\n   consumers and port 9300 to the elasticsearch namespace only.\n4. [HIGH-2,3] Remove privileged init container; apply pod security\n   context (runAsNonRoot, drop capabilities, seccomp).\n5. [MED-2] Complete or clean up the password rotation (elastic-password-next).\n6. [MED-4] Enable xpack.security.audit after re-enabling security.\n7. [LOW-1] Plan upgrade from 8.11.1 to current 8.x patch release.\n8. [MED-1] Configure backend TLS on the ingress → ES connection once\n   CRIT-2 is resolved, to achieve end-to-end encryption.\n\nNOTE: This audit is read-only. No cluster settings, secrets, indices,\nor Kubernetes resources were modified during this audit.\nFINDINGS_EOF\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with security findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1172,"cache_read_input_tokens":47676,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1172},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"86e97e24-746d-4c0c-a422-6f85b09b0af7","uuid":"4fd4d92b-688a-4511-9b01-f41c137ea260","request_id":"req_011Cc6pBb27xdWDVV3J9pQwQ"}
